    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Length Converter</h2>
      <p>
        Enter a numeric value in the input field and select the unit you are converting from using the dropdown. All eight length units update instantly, showing the equivalent value in millimeters, centimeters, meters, kilometers, inches, feet, yards, and miles. The converter uses the meter as the base unit internally, ensuring accurate conversions across all unit pairs.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool is useful for construction projects, international shipping dimensions, academic assignments, fitness tracking (miles vs. kilometers), and any scenario where you need to translate between metric and imperial length measurements quickly.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Metric vs. Imperial Length Units</h2>
      <p>
        The metric system uses a base-10 structure: 10 millimeters in a centimeter, 100 centimeters in a meter, and 1,000 meters in a kilometer. This decimal relationship makes mental arithmetic and scientific calculations straightforward. The imperial system, used primarily in the United States, Liberia, and Myanmar, uses less uniform ratios: 12 inches in a foot, 3 feet in a yard, and 1,760 yards (5,280 feet) in a mile.
      </p>

      <h3>Key Conversion Factors</h3>
      <p>
        The most commonly needed conversion factors are: 1 inch = 2.54 cm (exact), 1 foot = 0.3048 m (exact), 1 yard = 0.9144 m (exact), and 1 mile = 1.609344 km (exact). These definitions were internationally agreed upon in 1959, making them precise rather than approximate. For quick mental estimates: 1 meter is roughly 3 feet 3 inches, 1 kilometer is roughly 0.62 miles, and 1 mile is roughly 1.6 kilometers.
      </p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Unit</h3>
      <p>
        Use millimeters for precision engineering, jewelry, and small component measurements. Centimeters and inches work well for body measurements, clothing, and small objects. Meters and feet suit room dimensions, building plans, and human-scale measurements. Kilometers and miles are appropriate for road distances, running routes, and geographic scales. Matching the unit to the magnitude of the measurement keeps numbers readable and meaningful.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How many centimeters are in an inch?</h3>
      <p>
        One inch equals exactly 2.54 centimeters. This is an exact conversion defined by international agreement since 1959. To convert inches to centimeters, multiply by 2.54. To convert centimeters to inches, divide by 2.54.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert miles to kilometers?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the number of miles by 1.609344 to get kilometers. For example, 10 miles equals 16.09344 kilometers. Conversely, divide kilometers by 1.609344 to get miles. A quick mental approximation is that 1 mile is roughly 1.6 km.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between metric and imperial length units?</h3>
      <p>
        Metric units (mm, cm, m, km) are based on powers of 10, making conversions straightforward. Imperial units (inch, foot, yard, mile) use varying conversion factors: 12 inches per foot, 3 feet per yard, and 1,760 yards per mile. The metric system is used worldwide for science and in most countries for everyday measurement.
      </p>

      <h3>How many feet are in a meter?</h3>
      <p>
        One meter equals approximately 3.28084 feet. Conversely, one foot equals exactly 0.3048 meters. This conversion is exact by international definition, making foot-to-meter conversions precise.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert between millimeters and inches for precision work?</h3>
      <p>
        One inch equals exactly 25.4 millimeters. For precision engineering and machining, this exact conversion is critical. Multiply inches by 25.4 to get millimeters, or divide millimeters by 25.4 to get inches.
      </p>

